SECTION 3 — RFM Segmentation Framework

RFM segmentation allows us to tailor weekly campaigns based on customer lifecycle status.

3.1 RFM Segment Definitions

RECENCY (R)

How recently did the customer purchase?
	•	High Recency: Purchased in last 30 days
	•	Medium Recency: Purchased 31–90 days ago
	•	Low Recency: No purchase in 90+ days

FREQUENCY (F)

How often does the customer buy?
	•	High Frequency: 3+ purchases
	•	Medium Frequency: 2 purchases
	•	Low Frequency: 1 purchase

MONETARY (M)

How much have they spent?
	•	High Monetary: Top 20% spenders
	•	Mid Monetary: Middle 60%
	•	Low Monetary: Bottom 20%

⸻

3.2 RFM Customer Segments to Use in Campaign Planning

Segment	Definition	Messaging Approach	Offer Strategy
VIP / Champions	High R, High F, High M	Exclusive, early-access, insider	Early access, limited drops
Loyal Buyers	High R, Medium F	Appreciation, deepen loyalty	Bundles, cross-sells
High Potential	Medium R, High M	Re-engage with new products	Personalized recommendations
Warm Prospects (1X Buyers)	Medium R, Low F	Nurture, product education	New customer bundles
At-Risk	Low R, High F	Win-back messaging	Stronger incentives
Hibernating	Low R, Low F	Emotional reactivation angle	Win-back discount
New Customers	High R, Low F	Reinforce value	Post-purchase cross-sell


⸻

3.3 How RFM Influences Campaign Strategy

Messaging Style by Segment
	•	VIP: “You’re the first to get this…”
	•	Loyal: “Here’s something to make your next experience even better.”
	•	1X Buyers: “Here’s the next product people like you love.”
	•	At-Risk: “We miss you — here’s what’s new.”
	•	Hibernating: “Still thinking about you — here’s a reason to come back.”

Incentive Strategy by Segment
	•	VIP: Low or no discount, high exclusivity.
	•	Loyal: Bundle offers or loyalty incentives.
	•	1X Buyers: Entry-level incentives.
	•	At-Risk: Medium incentives.
	•	Hibernating: Your strongest offer (used sparingly).

